{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0283b811-3d0d-4e4a-9f73-fa1aec062dbd","content":"Use `dotnet watch test` — it monitors for file changes and automatically re-runs your tests:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch test --filter \"RemoveStock_ExceedsAvailable_ThrowsException\"\n```\n\nThe `--filter` flag scopes it to just your failing test for faster feedback. Once it's running, every time you save `InventoryServiceTests.cs`, the test re-runs automatically.\n\n**Quick diagnosis:** Your `RemoveStock` method doesn't validate quantity — it just subtracts without checking. It should throw when `quantity > available`. That's why the `ThrowsException<InvalidOperationException>` assertion fails.\n\nWant me to fix the `RemoveStock` method?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4eae9995-ebfb-46d5-925f-eafef8687d2f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to set up hot reload for the test project. Since this is using MSTest with Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner (as indicated by the global.json), they can use `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test`.\n\nLet me check what's available. With .NET 10 and Microsoft.Testing.Platform, `dotnet test` supports `--hotreload` natively. But also `dotnet watch test` works.\n\nThe best approach for rapid iteration is `dotnet watch test` which will re-run tests on file changes. Let me suggest that.\n\nActually, with the Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner in .NET 10, you can also use `dotnet test --hotreload` which uses hot reload to re-run tests without a full rebuild. \n\nI'll go with `dotnet watch test` since it's the more conventional approach for this workflow.","outputTokens":375,"requestId":"1BCB:C0207:2388219:274DC82:6A03DA56"},"id":"c005ba1c-6a56-46b0-86de-0cf444d35a54","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:56:47.543Z","parentId":"f65d1446-abb8-4056-ae34-e1b993d504d9"}
